Plugin Development Guide for GNU Midnight Commander
===================================================

This document describes how to create plugins from scratch for mc.
It focuses on practical implementation details for:

- panel plugins (filemanager virtual panels)
- editor plugins (mcedit extensions)

If you need API declarations, use these headers as source of truth:

- lib/panel-plugin.h
- lib/editor-plugin.h


1. Plugin Types
---------------

mc currently supports three plugin families:

- VFS plugins (virtual filesystems)
- Panel plugins (content providers for filemanager panels)
- Editor plugins (extensions for mcedit)

This guide focuses on panel/editor plugins. VFS has its own flow and is
not the preferred starting point for new UI-oriented features.


2. Common Rules
---------------

- Keep core plugin-agnostic.
  Do not require plugin-specific checks in filemanager/editor core.
- Use generic callback contracts from plugin headers.
- Return explicit status codes:
  - panel: MC_PPR_OK / MC_PPR_FAILED / MC_PPR_NOT_SUPPORTED
  - editor: MC_EPR_OK / MC_EPR_FAILED / MC_EPR_NOT_SUPPORTED
- Avoid shell string composition when a generic host callback exists.
  Example: panel diff should use host->open_diff().


3. Panel Plugins (Filemanager)
------------------------------

3.1 API Entry Point

A panel plugin module must export:

    const mc_panel_plugin_t *mc_panel_plugin_register (void);

The descriptor must have:

- api_version = MC_PANEL_PLUGIN_API_VERSION
- unique name
- required callbacks:
  - open()
  - close()
  - get_items()


3.2 Host Services Available to Plugin

From mc_panel_host_t:

- refresh(host)
- set_hint(host, text)
- message(host, flags, title, text)
- run_command(host, command, flags)
- open_diff(host, left_path, right_path)
- close_plugin(host, dir_path)
- get_marked_count(host)
- get_next_marked(host, &current)
- get_current(host)

Use open_diff() for two-file diff integration.


3.3 Minimal Panel Plugin Skeleton

Minimal structure:

- src/panel-plugins/myplugin/myplugin.c
- src/panel-plugins/myplugin/Makefile.am

Example descriptor:

```c
#include <config.h>
#include "lib/global.h"
#include "lib/panel-plugin.h"

static void *my_open (mc_panel_host_t *host, const char *open_path)
{
    (void) host;
    (void) open_path;
    return g_new0 (int, 1);
}

static void my_close (void *plugin_data)
{
    g_free (plugin_data);
}

static mc_pp_result_t my_get_items (void *plugin_data, void *list_ptr)
{
    (void) plugin_data;
    (void) list_ptr;
    return MC_PPR_OK;
}

static const mc_panel_plugin_t my_plugin = {
    .api_version = MC_PANEL_PLUGIN_API_VERSION,
    .name = "myplugin",
    .display_name = "My Plugin",
    .proto = "my",
    .prefix = "my:",
    .flags = MC_PPF_NONE,

    .open = my_open,
    .close = my_close,
    .get_items = my_get_items,
};

const mc_panel_plugin_t *
mc_panel_plugin_register (void)
{
    return &my_plugin;
}
```


3.4 Required get_items() Behavior

get_items(plugin_data, list) receives a dir_list* as opaque void*.

Important rule:

- Do not add ".." yourself.
  Core creates parent entry before calling plugin.


3.5 Optional Panel Callbacks

Navigation and actions:

- chdir(plugin_data, path)
- enter(plugin_data, fname, st)
- handle_key(plugin_data, key_or_command)
- create_item(plugin_data)                 (requires MC_PPF_CREATE)
- delete_items(plugin_data, names, count)  (requires MC_PPF_DELETE)
- get_local_copy(plugin_data, fname, &local_path)

UI integration:

- view(plugin_data, fname, st, plain_view)
- get_help_info(plugin_data, &filename, &node)
- get_title(plugin_data)
- get_columns(plugin_data, &count)
- get_column_value(plugin_data, fname, column_id)
- get_default_format(plugin_data)
- get_footer(plugin_data)
- get_focus_name(plugin_data)


3.6 Panel Build Integration

Plugin Makefile.am example:

```make
panelplugindir = $(panel_plugins_dir)
panelplugin_LTLIBRARIES = mc-panel-myplugin.la

mc_panel_myplugin_la_SOURCES = myplugin.c
mc_panel_myplugin_la_CPPFLAGS = $(GLIB_CFLAGS) -I$(top_srcdir)
mc_panel_myplugin_la_LDFLAGS = -module -avoid-version
mc_panel_myplugin_la_LIBADD = $(GLIB_LIBS)
```

Then include subdir:

- src/panel-plugins/Makefile.am: add SUBDIRS += myplugin
- configure.ac: add src/panel-plugins/myplugin/Makefile


4. Editor Plugins (mcedit)
--------------------------

4.1 API Entry Point

An editor plugin module must export:

    const mc_editor_plugin_t *mc_editor_plugin_register (void);

Required callbacks:

- open(host, editor_dialog)
- close(plugin_data)


4.2 Editor Callback Contract

Main optional callbacks:

- activate(plugin_data, edit)
  Main action entry (for Plugins menu command).
- configure(plugin_data, edit)
  Settings action (for Plugin info/configure flow).
- handle_action(plugin_data, command, edit)
  Command dispatcher for editor actions.
- query_state(plugin_data, edit, state)
  Availability/enabled/reason for menu and execution logic.
- handle_key(plugin_data, key, edit)
  Raw key handling.
- handle_event(plugin_data, edit, event_id, payload)
  Generic event channel.
- on_file_open(plugin_data, edit)
- on_file_close(plugin_data, edit)

State contract (mc_ep_state_t):

- available: plugin can operate in current environment
- enabled: action currently enabled
- reason: optional explanation shown to user


4.3 Editor Host Services

From mc_editor_host_t:

- refresh(host)
- message(host, flags, title, text)


4.4 Editor Build/Integration Modes

There are two practical ways to integrate editor plugin code:

- dynamic module (preferred for clean decoupling)
- in-tree builtin registration (used for transition/bootstrapping)

Dynamic mode requires module build/install to MC_EDITOR_PLUGINS_DIR.
Builtin mode registers descriptors from core startup code and links
plugin sources into editor library.

When adding a new plugin from scratch, prefer dynamic mode unless
project constraints require builtin linkage.


5. Help Integration
-------------------

Panel plugin help:

- implement get_help_info()
- return filename/node
- on MC_PPR_OK core opens that help node on F1

Editor plugin help/config UX:

- keep activate() for main action
- keep configure() for settings
- do not overload activate() with settings dialog


6. Key Handling Model
---------------------

Panel plugins:

- core first passes mapped command id to handle_key()
- if not handled and raw key differs, core retries with raw key

This allows either style:

- CK_* command based
- raw KEY_F(n) based

Editor plugins:

- use handle_action() for command semantics
- use handle_key() for direct key interception only when needed


7. Testing Checklist
--------------------

For panel plugins:

- plugin appears in Plugin panel menu
- prefix activation works (example: my:.)
- get_items() returns stable list and no duplicate ".."
- F3/F4/F5/F8 behavior is correct for plugin entries
- marked/current item flows work the same
- help opens plugin-specific node if provided

For editor plugins:

- plugin appears in editor plugin menu/info
- activate() runs primary action
- configure() opens settings only
- query_state() reflects backend/runtime availability
- missing dependencies are reported via clear user message


8. Troubleshooting
------------------

- Plugin not loaded:
  - verify module installed into correct plugin directory
  - verify exported symbol name (mc_panel_plugin_register or
    mc_editor_plugin_register)
  - verify api_version matches header constant

- Plugin listed but does nothing:
  - check required callbacks are non-NULL
  - confirm return codes (NOT_SUPPORTED vs FAILED)

- Key does not trigger:
  - confirm command mapping and raw key fallback path
  - verify plugin handle_key() compares against correct key ids


9. Notes on VFS Plugins
-----------------------

VFS plugin mechanism still exists and uses mc_vfs_plugin_init().
If you are implementing UI features, panel/editor plugins are usually
a better fit than adding new VFS classes.
